          "body": "Verse 2 is a diagnostic of Israel's spiritual condition: teraphim speak iniquity, diviners see lying visions, and the result is a people who 'wander like sheep, afflicted, because there is no shepherd.' The Hebrew hevel — the same word Qoheleth uses for 'vanity' — describes the false comfort offered: it is breath, vapor, nothing that holds. False shepherds are not merely ineffective; they are the active cause of the wandering. Verse 3 escalates the indictment: God's anger burns against the shepherds, and He will punish the male goats — the strong, dominant leaders who butted and scattered the weaker members of the flock (cf. Ezekiel 34:17-22). The pastoral imagery is deliberate and devastating: the leaders who were supposed to protect the flock from predators have become the source of harm. Ezekiel 34 is the canonical parallel — God's wrath against shepherds who feed themselves instead of the flock, followed by His own direct shepherding. Zechariah 10 picks up exactly where Ezekiel 34 left off."
