          "body": "Verses 6-7 announce what the eight-century-old division of the kingdom had made seem impossible: both the house of Judah and the house of Joseph will be saved and strengthened. The stated ground is not Israel's merit but God's compassion — 'because I have had compassion on them' (10:6). The restoration formula reaches its most remarkable expression in verse 6: 'they will be as though I had not rejected them.' This is not amnesia; it is covenant renewal so complete that the relational rupture of the exile is erased from the experiential record. Ephraim will be like a mighty man (gibbor, the warrior-word of verse 5), and the gladness will be generational — children will see it and rejoice (10:7). The joy is grounded, not in feelings, but in the Lord Himself: 'their heart will rejoice in the LORD.' John Calvin notes here that God's compassion is entirely from Himself — it finds no cause outside His own character. The restoration of both houses is not a reward; it is a revelation of who Yahweh is."
