          "body": "Verses 8-12 shift into the language of a second Exodus, with God as the sovereign Gatherer. He 'whistles' for His people (10:8) — the same verb used of summoning bees or commanding troops; it is a signal of absolute authority that is obeyed. The promise escalates: they will be as numerous as they were before (10:8), and even the scattering among the nations will have served His purpose — in far countries they will remember Him (10:9). The geographic scope broadens: from Egypt in the south, from Assyria in the north, into Gilead and Lebanon until there is no room (10:10). The obstacles — the sea, the depths of the Nile, the pride of Assyria, the scepter of Egypt — will all be struck down as God smashes whatever stands between His people and their land (10:11). The Exodus typology is explicit and cumulative: the sea is struck, the river dries up, the oppressor's power departs. Peter Davids and other commentators note that this New Exodus pattern is picked up in the NT — in John's Gospel with its Exodus motifs, in Paul's imagery of redemption (padah) as the ground of adoption, and in Revelation's portrayal of the final gathering. The chapter closes with a covenant-walk formula: 'they will walk in His name' (10:12) — restored identity, restored direction, sealed by the word of the LORD."
